Then $OP_1 = s/\sqrt{2},$ so $P_1 O P_2$ is a right isosceles triangle.  Then $P_2 O = P_3 O = s/\sqrt{2},$ so $P_2 O P_3$ is an equilateral triangle.  Hence, $s/\sqrt{2} = s,$ so $s = \boxed{\sqrt{2}}.$

Let $s$ be the side length of the octahedron.  Let $O$ be the center of the cube.  Let $A,$ $B,$ and $C$ be the centers of the faces of the cube that share a vertex with $P_1.$

